b2-3581.definition_en: To get involved or involve oneself, causing disturbance.

b2-3590.definition_en: To explain or tell the meaning of; to translate orally into intelligible or familiar language or terms. applied especially to language, but also to dreams, signs, conduct, mysteries, etc.

b2-3591.definition_en: An act of interpreting or explaining what is obscure; a translation; a version; a construction.
b2-3591.example_en: the interpretation of a dream, or of an enigma.

b2-3592.definition_en: One who conveys what a user of one language is saying or signing, in real time or shortly after that person has finished communicating, to a user of a different language. (Contrasted with a translator.)
b2-3592.example_en: A Japanese man who is tried before a German court is assisted by an interpreter in making oral statements.

b1-3593.definition_en: An event that causes a computer or other device to temporarily cease what it was doing and attend to a condition.
b1-3593.example_en: The interrupt caused the packet handler routine to run.

b2-3594.definition_en: The act of interrupting, or the state of being interrupted.

b2-3595.definition_en: The junction of two (or more) paths, streets, highways, or other thoroughfares.

b2-3604.definition_en: A dose of medicine administered from a drip, down through a hollow needle inserted into a patient's vein.
b2-3604.example_en: Get his morphine intravenous started stat!

a1-3605.definition_en: (of people) To cause (someone) to be acquainted (with someone else).

b2-3607.definition_en: To thrust oneself in; to come or enter without invitation, permission, or welcome; to encroach; to trespass.

b2-3609.definition_en: The forcible inclusion or entry of an external group or individual; the act of intruding.

b2-5182.definition_en: A crustacean of the suborder Dendrobranchiata.

a1-5183.definition_en: To direct words and/or thoughts to God or any higher being, for the sake of adoration, thanks, petition for help, etc.
a1-5183.example_en: Muslims pray in the direction of Mecca.

b1-5184.definition_en: A practice of communicating with one's God.
b1-5184.example_en: Through prayer I ask for God's blessings.

b2-5185.definition_en: Brief editorial preface (usually to an article or essay)

b1-5186.definition_en: Someone (or something) who is loved; a darling.

a2-5187.definition_en: (NNES or European Union documents) To make or render precise; to specify.

b2-5188.example_en: I always try to express myself precisely.

b2-5189.definition_en: A definite class, state or condition.

b2-5190.definition_en: (grammar) The part of the sentence (or clause) which states something about the subject or the object of the sentence.
b2-5190.example_en: In "The dog barked very loudly", the subject is "the dog" and the predicate is "barked very loudly".

b2-5191.definition_en: (grammar) An element of the predicate of a sentence which supplements the subject or object by means of the verb. Predicatives may be nominal or adjectival.

b2-5193.example_en: a boring film with a predictable ending

a2-5194.definition_en: A statement of what will happen in the future.

b2-5195.example_en: The amount of rain in April is predictive of the number of mosquitoes in May.

b2-5196.definition_en: Something that anticipates, predicts or foretells.
b2-5196.example_en: The predictor in the traffic-light control circuit tries to figure out how fast to change the lights.

b2-5197.definition_en: An official of Ancient Rome who controlled or superintended a particular command, charge, department, etc.
b2-5197.example_en: the prefect of the aqueducts; the prefect of a camp, of a fleet, of the city guard, or of provisions; the pretorian prefect, who was commander of the troops guarding the emperor's person

a2-5198.definition_en: To be in the habit of choosing something rather than something else; to favor; to like better.

b2-5199.definition_en: Better than some other option; preferred.

b2-5200.definition_en: In preference; by choice; in a preferable manner.

b1-5201.definition_en: The selection of one thing or person over others (with the main adposition being "for" in relation to the thing or person, but possibly also "of")
b1-5201.example_en: He has a preference for crisp wines.

b2-5204.definition_en: Having lasted from a remote period; having been of long duration; of great age, very old.
b2-5204.example_en: an ancient city an ancient forest

b2-5205.definition_en: One of the human-like creatures prior to Homo sapiens.

b2-5207.definition_en: To form a judgment of (something) in advance.

b1-5208.definition_en: An adverse judgment or opinion formed beforehand or without knowledge of the facts.

b2-5209.definition_en: A preparation for a main matter; an introduction.

b2-5210.definition_en: To distract; to occupy or draw attention elsewhere.
b2-5210.example_en: The father tried to preoccupy the child with his keys.

b1-5211.definition_en: The act of preparing or getting ready.
